I. Abstract
The geological and atmospheric characteristics of the Martian surface have been the subject of extensive scientific research, owing to their implications for future human exploration and settlement. This research aims to provide a comprehensive understanding of the Martian landscape, weather patterns, and potential resources, which are crucial for planning and executing manned missions (Grotzinger et al., 2012). The key findings of this study reveal that Mars harbors diverse geological features, including volcanoes, canyons, and polar ice caps, as well as a complex atmospheric system with seasonal variations (Jakosky & Phillips, 2020). The presence of water ice and other potential resources, such as methane and regolith, further highlight the planet's potential for human habitation (Lasue et al., 2013; Manning et al., 2014). These discoveries underscore the significance of Mars as a destination for human space exploration and the importance of continued research to support the development of sustainable human settlements on the Martian surface (Cockell et al., 2012).
