IV. Research Methodology
Research Methodology  This study employs a mixed-methods research design, combining both qualitative and quantitative data collection and analysis techniques to provide a comprehensive understanding of the geological and atmospheric characteristics of the Martian surface. The rationale for this approach is that it allows for a more holistic perspective on the subject matter, as well as the opportunity to triangulate data and validate findings (Creswell & Creswell, 2018).  Data Collection  For the quantitative component of this study, data was collected from various remote sensing instruments aboard NASA's Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter (MRO), Mars Express, and Mars Science Laboratory missions. These instruments include the High Resolution Imaging Science Experiment (HiRISE) camera, the Compact Reconnaissance Imaging Spectrometer for Mars (CRISM), and the Mars Science Laboratory's Chemistry and Camera (ChemCam) and Mastcam instruments (Bibring et al., 2010; Murchie et al., 2007; Wellington et al., 2017).  The qualitative component of this study involved a content analysis of existing scientific literature and mission reports related to Mars geology and atmospheric science. This analysis focused on identifying and categorizing key themes and findings related to the research question (Krippendorff, 2018).  Sampling Strategy and Participant Demographics  A purposive sampling strategy was employed for the quantitative data, with specific regions of interest (ROIs) selected based on their relevance to the research question. These ROIs included areas with evidence of water activity, such as recurring slope lineae (RSL) and ancient lake beds, as well as regions with significant geological features, such as volcanoes and impact craters (Edwards & Ehlmann, 2015; Grotzinger et al., 2015).  For the qualitative data, a snowball sampling strategy was used, with initial sources identified through a comprehensive literature search and subsequent sources identified through citation tracking and expert recommendations (Goodman, 1961).  Data Analysis Techniques and Software  Quantitative data analysis involved the use of statistical software, such as SPSS and R, to identify patterns and correlations within the data. Additionally, geographic information system (GIS) software, such as ArcGIS and QGIS, were used to visualize and analyze spatial data (ESRI, 2020; QGIS Development Team, 2020).  Qualitative data analysis involved a manual coding process, with codes and categories developed inductively from the data. The software NVivo was used to manage and organize the coding process (QSR International, 2020).  Ethical Considerations and Limitations  Ethical considerations in this study primarily involved ensuring compliance with relevant data use agreements and privacy policies related to the use of mission data and scientific literature. Additionally, efforts were made to minimize any potential harm or misinterpretation of findings through rigorous data analysis and transparent reporting practices (National Commission for the Protection of Human Subjects of Biomedical and Behavioral Research, 1979).  Limitations in this study include the reliance on remote sensing data, which may limit the accuracy and completeness of findings. Additionally, the use of a purposive sampling strategy may introduce bias into the data and limit the generalizability of findings (Creswell & Creswell, 2018).
