IV-A. Data Sources and Organization
In the study of the geological and atmospheric characteristics of the Martian surface, various data sources have been utilized to gather comprehensive and reliable information. These data sources can be categorized into primary and secondary sources.  Primary data sources refer to the direct observations and measurements obtained from various Martian missions, satellites, and rovers. Some of the key primary data sources include:  1. Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter (MRO): The MRO, launched in 2005, has been providing high-resolution imagery and data about the Martian surface, including information on geological features, landforms, and minerals (Malin & Edgett, 2010).  2. Mars Science Laboratory (MSL) - Curiosity Rover: The Curiosity rover, part of the MSL mission, has been gathering data on the Martian surface since its landing in 2012. It has provided valuable information on the composition of Martian rocks, soil, and the atmosphere (Grotzinger et al., 2012).  3. Mars Atmosphere and Volatile Evolution (MAVEN): MAVEN, launched in 2013, is studying the upper atmosphere of Mars to understand its climate change and the loss of its atmosphere to space (Jakosky et al., 2015).  Secondary data sources consist of processed and analyzed data from the primary sources, as well as information from scientific literature, reports, and reviews. These sources offer a synthesis of existing knowledge and help provide context for the interpretation of the primary data. Some secondary data sources include:  1. Planetary Data System (PDS): The PDS is a NASA-funded organization that archives and distributes scientific data from planetary missions, including Martian data (NASA, 2022).  2. Mars Exploration Program Analysis Group (MEPAG): MEPAG provides scientific and programmatic assessments of Mars exploration activities, offering a comprehensive perspective on the Martian surface and atmosphere (NASA, 2022).  The relevance and reliability of these data sources are established through their d