V. Results
The geological and atmospheric characteristics of the Martian surface have been the subject of extensive research, providing valuable insights for future human exploration and settlement.   In terms of geological characteristics, recent studies have revealed the presence of water-ice deposits at high latitudes (Michaels, 2020). These deposits could potentially be used as a water source for human consumption and life support systems. Furthermore, the discovery of recurring slope lineae (RSL), which are dark streaks appearing seasonally on Martian slopes, suggests the presence of liquid water in the past or potentially even in the present (Ojha et al., 2014).   [Image of RSL from Ojha et al., 2014]  The Martian atmosphere is primarily composed of carbon dioxide (CO2), with minor constituents including nitrogen, argon, oxygen, and trace amounts of carbon monoxide and water vapor (NASA, 2021). The atmospheric pressure on Mars is only about 1% that of Earth's sea level pressure, posing significant challenges for human habitation (Smith, 2004). However, the thin atmosphere does offer some advantages, such as reduced radiation exposure compared to space (Withers, 2012).  [Bar graph comparing atmospheric composition of Mars and Earth from NASA, 2021]  Temperature patterns on Mars exhibit significant diurnal and seasonal variations due to the planet's elliptical orbit and lack of a thick atmosphere (Vasavada & Manning, 2008). The average temperature on Mars is -80°F (-62°C), but temperatures can reach as high as 70°F (20°C) near the equator during midday and plummet to -220°F (-140°C) at night (Vasavada & Manning, 2008).   [Line graph showing temperature variations on Mars from Vasavada & Manning, 2008]  These geological and atmospheric findings highlight both the challenges and opportunities presented by Mars for future human exploration and settlement. While the thin atmosphere and extreme temperatures pose significant obstacles, the presence of water-ice deposits and the potential for liquid water offer promising resources for human survival.
